The '''2013 CECAFA Cup''' (known as the '''[[DStv|GOtv]] CECAFA Challenge Cup''' for sponsorship reasons)<ref name="Sponsors-1">{{cite news |url=http://www.kawowo.com/index.php/football/item/16564-go-tv-officially-announced-as-2013-cecafa-sponsors.html |title=GOtv unveiled as 2013 CECAFA Cup Official Sponsors |author=Ismael Kiyonga |publisher=Kawowo Sports |date=21 November 2013 |accessdate=22 November 2013}}</ref> was the 37th edition of the annual [[CECAFA Cup]], an international football competition consisting of the national teams of member nations of the [[Council for East and Central Africa Football Associations]] (CECAFA). The tournament was held in [[Kenya]] from 27 November to 12 December.

Contested by twelve national teams, the tournament had [[Zambia national football team|Zambia]] invited as a guest nation to fill in for [[Djibouti national football team|Djibouti]], who failed to participate for a second consecutive year. This followed the tournament's recent tradition of inviting other African nations to take part once a CECAFA nation pulled out; [[Malawi national football team|Malawi]] were invited to take part in the [[2012 CECAFA Cup|previous edition]] held in [[Uganda]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nyasatimes.com/malawi/2012/11/06/malawi-officially-invited-to-cecafa-cup-in-uganda/ |title=Malawi official invited to CECAFA Cup in Uganda |work=[[Nyasa Times]] |author=Elijah Phimbi |date=6 November 2012 |accessdate=6 November 2012 }}</ref> while they and [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]] took part in [[2011 CECAFA Cup|2011]] after [[Eritrea national football team|Eritrea]] withdrew from the competition.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.herald.co.zw/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=26733:warriors-get-cecafa-invitation&catid=50:sport&Itemid=142 |title=Warriors get Cecafa invitation |author=Grace Chingoma |work=The Herald |location=Zimbabwe |date=16 November 2011 |accessdate=20 November 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.starafrica.com/en/football/news/article/view/zimbabwe-replaces-namibia-for-cecafa-cup-204789.html |title=Zimbabwe replaces Namibia for CECAFA Cup |publisher=Star Africa |date=25 November 2011 |accessdate=25 November 2011 }}</ref>

Hosts [[Kenya national football team|Kenya]] ran out 2<U+2013>0 winners in the [[#Final|final]] against three-time champions [[Sudan national football team|Sudan]], with a brace from [[Allan Wanga]] securing the ''Harambee Stars'' their sixth title after losing to previous hosts [[Uganda national football team|Uganda]] at the same stage the [[2012 CECAFA Cup|previous year]].<ref name="Final summary 1">{{cite news |url=http://www.futaa.com/football/article/kenya-50-harambee-stars-wins-the-2013-cecafa-senior-challenge-cup |title=Kenya @50; Harambee Stars wins the 2013 CECAFA senior challenge Cup |author=Patrick Korir |publisher=Futaa.com |date=12 December 2013 |accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref><ref name="Final summary 2">{{cite news |url=https://www.radiodabanga.org/node/61546 |title=Kenya victorious over Sudan 2:0 in CECAFA 2013 |publisher=[[Radio Dabanga]] |date=12 December 2013 |accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref> The [[#Third place playoff|third place playoff]] was won by guests Zambia, who beat [[Tanzania national football team|Tanzania]] 6<U+2013>5 on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]] after playing out to a 1<U+2013>1 draw after 90 minutes.<ref name="Third place summary">{{cite news |url=http://www.futaa.com/football/article/gotv-cecafa-zambia-beat-tanzania-to-emerge-third |title=GOtv CECAFA: Zambia beat Tanzania to emerge third |author=Brian Moseti |publisher=Futaa.com |date=12 December 2013 |accessdate=30 January 2015}}</ref>

==Background and sponsorship==
On 25 November 2012, it was announced that Kenya was chosen to host the tournament after bids were placed by the host nation as well as [[Rwanda]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.starafrica.com/football/kenya-to-host-2013-cecafa-challenge-cup.html |title=Kenya to host 2013 Cecafa Challenge Cup |author=Fred Maingi |date=25 November 2012 |work=StarAfrica |accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> However, their hosting of the tournament was not confirmed until a congress meeting for the [[Confederation of African Football]] held in [[Marrakesh]], [[Morocco]] on 11 March 2013, after it was announced that the [[Football Kenya Federation]] had met all the requirements for hosting the tournaments with support from the [[Government of Kenya|Kenyan government]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.goal.com/en-ke/news/4522/kenya/2013/03/11/3816488/kenya-wins-bid-to-host-2013-cecafa-tournament |title=Kenya wins bid to host 2013 Cecafa tournament |author=Dennis Mabuka |work=[[Goal.com]] |date=11 March 2013 |accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> The capital city [[Nairobi]], [[Mombasa]], [[Kisumu]], [[Machakos]] and [[Nakuru]] were identified as host cities for the tournament.<ref name="Initial dates">{{cite news |url=http://www.kawowo.com/index.php/football/item/16215-cecafa-announce-cecafa-dates.html |title=2013 Cecafa Senior Challenge Cup Kicks Off November 27 |author=Ismael Kiyonga |date=1 October 2013 |work=Kawowo Sports |location=Uganda |accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref>

On 21 November 2013, CECAFA announced that [[DStv|GOtv]] would be the title sponsors of the tournament, having committed [[Kenya shilling|Ksh.]] 11.25 million towards the organisation of the event and a further Ksh. 45 million towards the broadcasting of all 26 matches. Other companies that were sponsoring the tournament were [[The Coca-Cola Company|Coca-Cola]], who committed Ksh. 6.5 million, and UAP Insurance, who committed Ksh. 5.5 million.<ref name="Sponsors-1" /><ref name="Sponsors-2">{{cite news |url=http://www.goal.com/en-ke/news/5231/featured-story/2013/11/21/4422289/cecafa-unveil-gotv-as-title-sponsors-for-tournament |title=Cecafa unveil GOtv as title sponsors for tournament |author=Otieno Otieno |publisher=[[Goal.com]] |date=21 November 2013 |accessdate=22 November 2013}}</ref><ref name="Sponsors-3">{{cite news |url=http://www.michezoafrika.com/cecafa/gotv-officially-unveiled-as-cecafa-title-sponsors/14899 |title=Gotv officially unveiled as CECAFA title Sponsors |author=Dennis Machio |publisher=MichezoAfrika.com |date=21 November 2013 |accessdate=22 November 2013}}</ref>

Of Ksh. 8.7 million (approx. [[United States dollar|US$]] 100,000) that was allocated for prize money, the winners were to receive Ksh. 5.6 million, while the runners-up were to take home Ksh. 2.5 million. The [[#Third place playoff|third place playoff]] winners were to receive Ksh. 600,000.<ref name="Sponsors-3" />

==Participants==
The draw for teams to participate in the tournament was held during the tournament's launch on 15 November 2013.<ref name="Tournament launch">{{cite news |url=http://www.futaa.com/football/article/cecafa-2013-set-for-official-launch |title=CECAFA 2013 set for official launch |author=Wilson Mathu |publisher=Futaa.com |date=12 November 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref><ref name="Tournament draw-1">{{cite news |url=http://www.futaa.com/football/article/cecafa-stars-cranes-land-different-groups |title=CECAFA: Stars', Cranes land different groups |author=Wilson Mathu |publisher=Futaa.com |date=15 November 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref><ref name="Tournament draw-2">{{cite news |url=http://kpl.co.ke/news/article/131115/Rivals_Kenya_Uganda_kept_apart_in_Cecafa_draw |title=Rivals Kenya, Uganda kept apart in Cecafa draw |publisher=[[Kenyan Premier League|KPL]].co.ke |date=15 November 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref> Alongside the 12 member nations of CECAFA, [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]], [[Malawi national football team|Malawi]] and [[Zambia national football team|Zambia]] were initially mooted as invitees for the tournament.<ref name="Guests">{{cite news |url=http://www.cafonline.com/football/news/18355-cecafa-to-invite-malawi-zambia-and-ivory-coast-for-2013-senior-challenge-cup.html |title=CECAFA to invite Malawi, Zambia and Ivory Coast for 2013 Senior Challenge Cup |publisher=[[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] Online |date=10 September 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140222181501/http://www.cafonline.com/football/news/18355-cecafa-to-invite-malawi-zambia-and-ivory-coast-for-2013-senior-challenge-cup.html |archivedate=22 February 2014}}</ref> However, CECAFA decided against inviting the Ivory Coast, with Secretary-General Nicholas Musonye saying that flying in ''Les <U+00C9>l<U+00E9>phants'' and keeping them in the country would cost the organisers over [[United States dollar|US$]] 25,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.futaa.com/football/article/cecafa-2013-no-ivory-coast-show |title=CECAFA 2013: No Ivory Coast show |author=Dan Ngulu |publisher=Futaa.com |date=12 October 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref>  The [[Football Association of Malawi]] decided not to enter a team for the tournament due to a lack of funds.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nyasatimes.com/2013/10/10/malawi-pulls-out-of-cecafa-senior-challenge-cup/ |title=Malawi pulls out of Cecafa Senior Challenge Cup |author=Agencies |work=Nyasa Times |date=10 October 2013 |accessdate=20 November 2013 }}</ref>

